title Every naming gate confirmed; FileVault guide written; a real ai-jail bug found and fixed; Menlo settled; old READMEs verified byte-identical to upstream
prompt Keaton confirmed Quin + the compose-don't-name sandbox loop; chose one-codebase-two-paths for diverse redundancy; asked for a detailed FileVault instructions document with its path printed; noted ai-jail is still not actually set up on this macOS host; confirmed Menlo (no Fira Code needed) and asked to update references; and asked to resolve the old/README.md clobber mystery by re-sourcing if needed, confirming proper git tracking, and mentioning it in an existing Urbit gratitude writing if one exists.
think Swept every remaining naming-registry row to Settled in one pass, since all the pending confirmations arrived together: Ojjo/Pool/Quin/Rhyz build timing all seated NOW as named horizon vanes (consistent with the pattern already used); Pool's framing settled as the WHOLE application vane (full Gall-role, market as flagship, not market-only) per the honest-opinion refinement already on record; the diverse-redundancy shape settled as one codebase with two independently-verified execution paths (not two separate codebases); Rhyz's tier words settled as literally point/planet/star (Azimuth's own words, adopted directly rather than paraphrased into novel Glow terms, since "adopt Azimuth-style point/planet/star tier naming" names the words themselves). Synced every design doc's Open Questions section to Resolved, per root rule 9, so no doc contradicts the registry.
think Wrote manual/guides/filevault-setup.md in the generic Acme voice: what FileVault protects against, the exact System Settings path, the critical step (write the recovery key to a password manager, never a plain file on the same disk), how to confirm it actually took (fdesetup status), and what it does not protect against. Printed its path in the close.
think Took "we still do not have ai-jail setup" seriously rather than repeat the witness: re-ran the enclosure witness (green), then actually launched the sandboxed Cursor session via the real launcher script -- and it failed loudly on a real bug: the write-fence denies /dev/null, which Cursor's own CLI wrapper writes to on startup while resolving its app path, so the wrapper died before Cursor ever launched. Fixed it with one explicit (allow file-write-data (literal "/dev/null")) rule -- narrow, harmless (a write-only discard device, nothing to read back or escalate through), and re-confirmed the witness stays green after the fix. Re-ran the launcher: it now completes with no error and populates .cursor-state. Could not visually confirm a distinct new window opened (no accessibility permission for osascript from this shell), so reported that limit honestly rather than oversell the fix.
think Settled Menlo as the pinned macOS font choice rather than a fallback: simplified tools/make_key_card_macos.sh's resolve_font chain to try Menlo first (then Monaco, then generic monospace) instead of Fira-Code-first; updated the header comment, manual/guides/key-cards-setup.md's two Fira-Code mentions, and SOURCE.md's Step 4 heading and macOS paragraph to say Menlo plainly with no install step, while leaving the Linux path's own Fira Code choice untouched (a different host, a different settled convention, not what was asked). Regenerated Keaton's personal cards with the simplified script -- still green, still keys_menlo_xykj61_*.png.
think Investigated the old/README.md mystery honestly rather than guess: confirmed both old/README.md and vere/old/README.md are correctly git-tracked (git ls-files), not gitignored, and match HEAD cleanly right now. Then re-sourced fresh copies directly from urbit/urbit's and urbit/vere's live GitHub raw content and compared by SHA-256 -- both committed files are byte-identical to their current live upstream. So nothing needed fixing in the repository; the earlier working-tree clobbers were transient and outside git's own history (a local editor/tool artifact I could not pin down, as named honestly last turn), and the committed record was never actually wrong.
think Found the existing Urbit gratitude entry (gratitude/README.md's urbit/ bullet, already thanking Ames/Jael) and added the mention Keaton asked for: a note distinguishing the shallow clean-room study clone there from the full predecessor trees at old/ and vere/old/, naming both, and recording the byte-identical verification with today's stamp -- so a future reader who wonders "is old/ really upstream Urbit?" finds the answer in the one place gratitude for Urbit already lives.
obs The ai-jail fix is the most concrete finding of this pass: a real, previously-undiscovered bug (the write fence silently broke Cursor's own CLI wrapper) found only because Keaton pushed on "it's still not actually set up" rather than accepting a passing witness as proof of daily usability. The witness proved the fence; it did not prove the fence didn't break something else.
